====International====
Oliver typewriter designs were licensed for production in several countries.  Variants of model No. 3 were produced by The Linotype Company of [[Montreal, Canada|Montreal]] and A. Greger & Co. of [[Vienna]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://etceterarehr1.googlepages.com/ETC.04.pdf |title = Oddest of Olivers? | author = Decker, Don| publisher= [http://staff.xu.edu/~polt/typewriters/etc.html ETCetera] &ndash; Magazine of the Early Typewriter Collectors Association |date = July 1988 | pages = p. 1 |format=[[PDF]] |accessdate= 2008-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last = Frey | first = E.| title = Luegers Lexikon der gesamten Technik und ihrer Hilfswissenschaften | publisher = Deutsche Verlags-Anstalt | date = 1926 | pages = p. 117 | language= German}}</ref>  Models produced by licensees were marketed under various names including <U+201C>Courier<U+201D> ([[Austria]]), "Fiver" (Germany),<ref name="adler"/> <U+201C>Stolzenberg<U+201D> (continental Europe) and <U+201C>Revilo<U+201D> ([[Argentina]]).<ref name="successor"/>  Revilo, Oliver backwards, was used to avoid [[Royalties|royalty payment]]s on the Oliver name, which had already been registered.<ref>{{cite book| last = Hammerton | first = John Alexander | title = The Real Argentine: Notes and Impressions of a Year in the Argentine and Uruguay | publisher = Dodd, Mead and Company | date = 1915 | pages = pp. 228-229 }}</ref>

